27 (1) the Legislature to provide by law for increasing the required number of such
28 sites; and (2) a county clerk to establish any additional number of such sites.
1 RESOLVED BY THE SENATE AND ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF
2 NEVADA, JOINTLY, That a new section, designated Section 11, be
3 added to Article 2 of the Nevada Constitution to read as follows:
4 Sec. 11. 1. The county clerk shall send to each active
5 registered voter in the county who is eligible to vote in an
6 election a mail ballot. Mail ballots must be sent:
7 (a) On or after the fifth Monday before the election but
8 not later than the fourth Monday before the election to
9 active registered voters who reside within the State; and
10 (b) On or after the seventh Monday before the election
11 but not later than the fifth Monday before the election to
12 active registered voters who reside outside the State unless
13 federal or state law requires mail ballots be sent earlier to
14 active registered voters who reside outside the State.
15 2. If a person registers to vote or updates his or her
16 voter registration information not later than 14 days before
17 the election, the county clerk shall send a mail ballot to that
18 person unless a mail ballot has been sent by the county
19 clerk pursuant to subsection 1.
20 3. Notwithstanding the provisions of subsections 1 and
21 2, a county clerk shall allow a voter to elect not to receive a
22 mail ballot by submitting to the county clerk a written notice
23 in a form prescribed by the county clerk. The notice must be
24 received by the county clerk not later than 60 days before
25 the day of the election.
26 4. A mail ballot must include all offices, candidates
27 and measures upon which the voter is entitled to vote at the
28 election.
29 5. Except as otherwise required by federal or state law,
30 the county clerk shall send to each active registered voter
31 eligible to cast a vote but who has not elected under
32 subsection 3 not to receive a mail ballot, by first-class mail
33 or by any class of mail if the Official Election Mail logo or
34 an equivalent mark created by the United States Postal
35 Service is properly placed:
36 (a) A mail ballot;
37 (b) A return envelope;
38 (c) An envelope or sleeve into which the mail ballot is
39 inserted to ensure its secrecy; and
40 (d) Instructions.
